Will has said in interviews before that even tho he regrets missing the matrix, he is also glad. He said one time, at that point in his career, he was too young and cocky to really let Neo become what Neo ultimately became, and he said that Keanu did a far better job then he would have done.

How about this, Bruce Willis was basically last, a backup, for a diehard. They wanted Stallon, and then Arnold, and then Kurt Russel. Willis was a nobody at the time. But thank god.. I mean Die Hard transformed the action movie genre, it was the first action movie to have comedy. Like instead of stallon or arnold just some big unstoppable muscle dude saying almost nothing, you have a kinda funny but badass dude kickin ass. Die Hard is the transition from 80s action to modern action.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm thinking about the biggest movie stars of the past 25 years. DiCaprio, Clooney, Pitt, Smith, Depp, Cruise.

I think it's a contest between Cruise and Smith for who's the better hype man and salesman. Smith always gives it his 110% trying to sell his movies and keeping it upbeat, positive, etc. People probably don't realize this and think it's just all natural, but this takes conscious effort. When I was a teenager, I would describe behavior like this as "fake" or "selling out", but now I just see a dude who's fucking hustling and doing his best to sell himself and his work. He's busting his ass.

Just for that constant and never-ending hustle, Will Smith deserves major respect.
